########################################################################

DOCUMENT();      

loadMacros(
   "PGstandard.pl",     # Standard macros for PG language
   "MathObjects.pl",
   #"source.pl",        # allows code to be displayed on certain sites.
   "PGcourse.pl",      # Customization file for the course
   "parserFormulaUpToConstant.pl",
   "parserFormulaWithUnits.pl",
   "parserNumberWithUnits.pl",
   "weightedGrader.pl",
   "answerHints.pl",
   "Alfredmacros.pl"
);
jsmathmode();
install_weighted_grader();


# Print problem number and point value (weight) for the problem
TEXT(beginproblem());

# Show which answers are correct and which ones are incorrect
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

##############################################################
#
#  Setup
#
#
Context("Numeric");
Context()->variables->are(t=>"Real",dt=>"Real");

$g =Compute("-9.81");
$a = NumberWithUnits("$g","m/s^2");
$v0 =  Compute(random(20,40));
$vinit = NumberWithUnits("$v0","m/s");

$vel = Formula("$g*t+$v0");
$v = FormulaWithUnits("$vel","m/s");

$timezero = Compute("-$v0/$g");   # more than 2, less than 5
$t = NumberWithUnits("$timezero","s"); 

$time0 = Compute(random(0,2,.25));
$time1 = Compute(random(3,5,.25));

$t0 = NumberWithUnits("$time0","s");
$t1 = NumberWithUnits("$time1","s");

$vt0 = $vel->substitute(t=>"$time0");
$vt1 = $vel->substitute(t=>"$time1");

$FTC = FormulaWithUnits("$vt1-$vt0","m/s");

##############################################################
#
#  Text
#
#

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
For this problem, upward will be considered the positive direction. The acceleration due to gravity is \($a\).
$BR
$BR
The general equation for the velocity of an object tossed upward is
\(v = \int\)\{ans_rule(10)\} = \{ans_rule\}.
$BR
All of your answers from here (except the equation to find when the velocity is zero) require \{ helpLink('units') \}.
$BR
$BR
If a ball is tossed upward with initial velocity \($vinit\), then we can find the unknown constant C. In this case, \(v = \) \{ans_rule\}. 
$BR
The net change in the ball's velocity from time \($t0\) to time \($t1\) is 
$BR
\(
\begin{aligned}
v(\hbox{\{$t1->ans_rule(2)\}})-v(\hbox{\{$t0->ans_rule(2)\}}) = 
\int_{\hbox{\{$t0->ans_rule(2)\}}}^{\hbox{\{$t1->ans_rule(2)\}}} \hbox{\{ans_rule(10)\}}\hskip 5pt dt =& \hbox{\{ans_rule\}}\Big\vert_\hbox{\{$t0->ans_rule(2)\}}^\hbox{\{$t1->ans_rule(2)\}}\\
&\\
=&\hbox{\{ans_rule(13)\}}
\end{aligned}
\)
$BR
$BR
To find the time at which the ball reaches its maximum height, we must solve the equation \{ans_rule(8)\} = 0, which gives \(t = \) \{$t->ans_rule(6)\}. 
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

##############################################################
#
#  Answers
#
#

ANS(Formula("$g*dt")->cmp()->withPostFilter(AnswerHints(
                $g => "You seem to have forgotten dt.")));
ANS(FormulaUpToConstant("$g*t")->cmp());
ANS($v->cmp());

#net change in velocity
ANS($t1->cmp());
ANS($t0->cmp());
ANS($t0->cmp());
ANS($t1->cmp());
ANS($a->cmp());
ANS(FormulaWithUnits("$g*t","m/s")->cmp());
ANS($t0->cmp());
ANS($t1->cmp());
ANS($FTC->cmp());

#find when velocity is zero
ANS($vel->cmp());
ANS($t->cmp());
ENDDOCUMENT();        